We will call our given number of neutrons at the start (when t = 0),
$P_0$. Note that when we calculate the number of neutrons at the start,
we get $P(0) = 1$. So in order for our function $P(t)$ to give us the
starting number of neutrons, $P_0$, we need to multiply $e^{10^8t}$ by
$P_0$ to get our final formula, $P(t) = P_0e^{10^8t}$.

To calculate how long it takes for the neutrons to double, we set our
function $P(t)$ equal to double the starting amount, or $2P_0$. This
gives us

\begin{align*}
2P_0 = P_0e^{10^8t}
\end{align*}

After canceling the $P_0$ from both sides, taking a natural logarithm of
both sides, and simplifying using log rules we get

\begin{align*}
\ln(2) = \ln(e^{10^8t})
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle \ln(2) = 10^8t
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
\frac{\ln(2)}{10^8} = t
\end{align*}
